Datasets¶

We start by making a synthetic dataset of 2000 instances and five classes, with 400 instances in each class. (See https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/generated/sklearn.datasets.make_blobs.html regarding how the data are generated.) We choose to use a synthetic dataset---and not a set of natural occuring data---because we are mostly interested in properties of the various learning algorithms, in particular the differences between linear classifiers and multi-layer neural networks together with the difference between binary and multi-class data. In addition, we would like a dataset with instances represented with only two numerical features, so that it is easy to visualize the data. It would be rather difficult (although not impossible) to find a real-world dataset of the same nature. Anyway, you surely can use the code in this assignment for training machine learning models on real-world datasets.

When we are doing experiments in supervised learning, and the data are not already split into training and test sets, we should start by splitting the data. Sometimes there are natural ways to split the data, say training on data from one year and testing on data from a later year, but if that is not the case, we should shuffle the data randomly before splitting. (OK, that is not necessary with this particular synthetic data set, since it is already shuffled by default by Scikit-Learn, but that will not be the case with real-world data) We should split the data so that we keep the alignment between X (features) and t (class labels), which may be achieved by shuffling the indices. We split into 50% for training, 25% for validation, and 25% for final testing. The set for final testing must not be used till the end of the assignment in part 3.

We fix the seed both for data set generation and for shuffling, so that we work on the same datasets when we rerun the experiments. This is done by the random_state argument and the rng = np.random.RandomState(2024).

Linear regression¶

We see that even the binary set (X, t2) is far from linearly separable, and we will explore how various classifiers are able to handle this. We start with linear regression with the Mean Squared Error (MSE) loss, although it is not the most widely used approach for classification tasks: but we are interested. You may make your own implementation from scratch or start with the solution to the weekly exercise set 7. We include it here with a little added flexibility.

In [9]:
def add_bias(X, bias):
    """X is a NxM matrix: N datapoints, M features
    bias is a bias term, -1 or 1, or any other scalar. Use 0 for no bias
    Return a Nx(M+1) matrix with added bias in position zero
    """
    N = X.shape[0]
    biases = np.ones((N, 1)) * bias # Make a N*1 matrix of biases
    # Concatenate the column of biases in front of the columns of X.
    return np.concatenate((biases, X), axis  = 1)

class NumpyLinRegClass(NumpyClassifier):

    def __init__(self, bias=-1):
        self.bias=bias
    
    def fit(self, X_train, t_train, eta = 0.1, epochs=10):
        """X_train is a NxM matrix, N data points, M features
        t_train is avector of length N,
        the target class values for the training data
        lr is our learning rate
        """
        
        if self.bias:
            X_train = add_bias(X_train, self.bias)
            
        (N, M) = X_train.shape
        
        self.weights = weights = np.zeros(M)
        
        for epoch in range(epochs):
            # print("Epoch", epoch)
            weights -= eta / N *  X_train.T @ (X_train @ weights - t_train)      
    
    def predict(self, X, threshold=0.5):
        """X is a KxM matrix for some K>=1
        predict the value for each point in X"""
        if self.bias:
            X = add_bias(X, self.bias)
        ys = X @ self.weights
        return ys > threshold

In [14]:
def plot_decision_regions(X, t, clf=[], size=(8,6)):
    """Plot the data set (X,t) together with the decision boundary of the classifier clf"""
    # The region of the plane to consider determined by X
    x_min, x_max = X[:, 0].min() - 1, X[:, 0].max() + 1
    y_min, y_max = X[:, 1].min() - 1, X[:, 1].max() + 1
    
    # Make a prediction of the whole region
    h = 0.02  # step size in the mesh
    xx, yy = np.meshgrid(np.arange(x_min, x_max, h), np.arange(y_min, y_max, h))
    Z = clf.predict(np.c_[xx.ravel(), yy.ravel()])
    # Classify each meshpoint.
    Z = Z.reshape(xx.shape)

    plt.figure(figsize=size) # You may adjust this

    # Put the result into a color plot
    plt.contourf(xx, yy, Z, alpha=0.2, cmap = 'Paired')

    plt.scatter(X[:,0], X[:,1], c=t, s=10.0, cmap='Paired')

    plt.xlim(xx.min(), xx.max())
    plt.ylim(yy.min(), yy.max())
    plt.title("Decision regions")
    plt.xlabel("x0")
    plt.ylabel("x1")

ANS¶

For this task, I set the no_etas/no_epochs = 20. This means we tested out 20x20 combinations in tuning the etas/epochs. Initially, I did this manually by varying the etas epochs and plotted the decision boundary along with the accuracy. This manual tuning by sight worked for tuning a small samples of hyperparameters. The tuning function below more or less automatizes this process of tuning and returns values of etas and epochs which produces the highest accuracy. Ofc, this function is restricted to picking the first eta- and epoch-values which yields the highest accuracy, meaning that other combinations of eta- and epoch-values resulting in the same highscore of accuracy are ommitted. I commented out the print-function inside the for-loop that can be used to find the current eta and epoch their respective score, and print only the first combination resulting in an accuracy highscore. In our case, the optimal hyperparameters are: eta = 0.031 & epoch = 684, which result in an accuracy of 0.76 > 0.58. This is a whole other magnitude of improvement and displays the power of tuning the hyperparameters, though this can be exhaustive if done manually. As for the decision boundary below, we see that the oblique decision border crosses a little bit off from the most dense areas of the red class. The occurences of the other class is mainly above the red class. Ofc, this decision border is not ideal as the classification problem is not linearly separable.

For tuning the linreg classifier, we use following values:

  • min_eta=1e-03, max_eta=5e-2,
  • min_epoch=1, max_epoch=4000

Note: the optimal eta and epoch vary from run to run

In [16]:
def tuning(cl, X_train, t_train, X_val, t_val, min_eta, max_eta, min_epoch, max_epoch, num_etas=20, num_epochs=20):
    """
    Finds the learning rate (eta) and number of epochs for the given model `cl`
    which returns the highest accuracy.
    For tuning we use following values:
    min_eta=1e-03, max_eta=5e-2, 
    min_epoch=1, max_epoch=4000
    """
    etas = np.random.uniform(low=min_eta, high=max_eta, size=num_etas)                # Random 20 learning rates, 
    epochs = np.linspace(start=min_epoch, stop=max_epoch, num=num_epochs, dtype=int)  # Divide epochs into 20 evenly spaced values
    
    best_eta = None
    best_epoch = None
    highest_accuracy = 0  # Initialize with the lowest possible accuracy = 0
    
    for eta in etas:
        for epoch in epochs:
            # Fit the model with the current eta and epoch values
            cl.fit(X_train, t_train, eta=eta, epochs=epoch)
            
            # Predict on the validation set
            t_pred = cl.predict(X_val)  
            
            # Calculate accuracy on the validation set
            accuracy = np.mean(t_pred == t_val)  
            
            # Update the best values if the current accuracy(eta & epoch) is better
            if accuracy > highest_accuracy:
                highest_accuracy = accuracy
                best_eta = round(eta, 3)
                best_epoch = epoch
                
            #print(f"eta: {eta}, epoch: {epoch}, Accuracy: {accuracy}")  # Debugging output
    
    print(f"Best eta: {best_eta}, Best epoch: {best_epoch}, Highest Accuracy: {highest_accuracy}")
    return best_eta, best_epoch

cl = NumpyLinRegClass()
best_eta, best_epoch = tuning(cl, X_train, t2_train, X_val, t2_val, min_eta=1e-03, max_eta=5e-2, min_epoch=1, max_epoch=4000)

cl.fit(X_train, t2_train, eta = best_eta, epochs=best_epoch)
print("Accuracy on the validation set:", accuracy(cl.predict(X_val), t2_val))

#Our class that scales the data(X) -> normalize the data
class StandardScaler():
    def fit(self, X):
        self.mean = X.mean(axis = 0)
        self.std = X.std(axis = 0)
    
    def transform(self,X):
        return (X-self.mean)/self.std
    
# Transforming X_train to a scaled set of data
sc = StandardScaler()
sc.fit(X_train)                     # Just fit the scaler

ANS:¶

We can see from the tuning of parameters for both the scaled and unscaled data sets, that the accuracy from the training data on the validation set results in almost the same accuracy (~0.76). The training on the scaled data resulted in a slightly higher score of 0.762 as it was 0.76 for the non-scaled training data. Furthermore we have the following hyper-parameters:

  • Non-scaled data: eta = 0.048 & epoch = 421,
  • Scaled data: eta = 0.015 & epoch = 211

Using the no. of epochs as an estimation for runtime of the training, we see that the training on scaled data is equally fast as the training on the non-scaled data, but on the other hand, it operates with a smaller eta, i.e. 0.004 < 0.029, and the training converges equally as fast. This means that scaling the training data results in a shorter training session as well as a slight improvement of accuracy!

def logistic(X):
    return 1/(1+np.exp(-X))

def MSE(y, y_pred):
    return np.mean((y-y_pred)**2)

'Part a)'
class NumpyLogRegClass(NumpyClassifier):

    def __init__(self, bias=-1):
        self.bias=bias

#Picked an arbitrary high value for epochs=10000, eta and tol are later changed during the tuning_function
    def fit(self, X_train, t_train, val_set=None, eta=0.1, epochs=10000, tol=0.0001, n_epochs_no_update=5):
    
        (N, m) = X_train.shape
        X_train = add_bias(X_train, self.bias)
        self.weights = weights = np.zeros(m + 1)

        threshold = 0.5

        # Initialize metrics storage
        'Part c)'
        self.list_acc = []           # Store training accuracies
        self.list_mse = []           # Store training MSE loss
        'Part d)'
        self.list_val_acc = []       # Store validation accuracies
        self.list_val_mse = []       # Store validation MSE loss

        'Part e)'
        self.no_epochs_training = [] # Store epoch numbers
        self.n_epochs_trained = 0    # Attribute to store number of epochs trained for
        epochs_since_update = 0      # Track how many epochs since last significant improvement in loss

        for epoch in range(epochs):
            self.no_epochs_training.append(epoch)
            
           
            y_pred = self.forward(X_train)                       #Our predictions
            weights -= eta / N * X_train.T @ (y_pred - t_train)  # Gradient descent weight update

            # Compute training accuracy and MSE
            'Part c)'
            self.list_mse.append(MSE(t_train, y_pred))
            self.list_acc.append(accuracy((y_pred > threshold).astype('int'), t_train))

            'Part d)'
            # If validation set is provided, compute validation metrics
            if val_set is not None:
                X_val, t_val = val_set
                X_val_bias = add_bias(X_val, self.bias)
                y_val_pred = self.forward(X_val_bias)

                # Compute validation accuracy and MSE
                self.list_val_mse.append(MSE(t_val, y_val_pred))
                self.list_val_acc.append(accuracy((y_val_pred > threshold).astype('int'), t_val))

            'Part e): Early stopping condition'
            if len(self.list_mse) >= n_epochs_no_update:
                # Check the last n_epochs_no_update values of the training loss
                recent_mse = self.list_mse[-n_epochs_no_update:]
                mse_diff = np.diff(recent_mse)
                
                # If the changes in MSE are all less than the tolerance, stop training
                if np.all(np.abs(mse_diff) < tol):
                    #print(f"Stopping early at epoch {epoch+1} due to no significant improvement in loss.")
                    break  # Stop training
            
     
            epochs_since_update += 1

        
        self.n_epochs_trained = epoch + 1   # Store the number of epochs the model actually trained for
      
               

    def forward(self, X):
        return logistic(X @ self.weights)
    
    def predict(self, X, threshold=0.5):
        """X is a Kxm matrix for some K>=1
        predict the value for each point in X"""
        z = add_bias(X, self.bias)
        return (self.forward(z) > threshold).astype('int')
    
    'Part b)'
    def predict_probability(self, X):
        z = add_bias(X, self.bias)
        return self.forward(z)


'Part f)'
'The logistic function'
def tune_logistic_regression(cl, X_train, t_train, X_val, t_val, n_epochs_no_update=5, is_data_scaled=False):
  
#Predefined list of eta and tol values to tune


    #Ideal for nonscaled-training data
    #Use cases here to because dim of lists affects the output graphs for scaled training data
    if is_data_scaled == False:
        eta_values = [5**(-i) for i in range(8)]
        tol_values = [5**(-i) for i in range(8)]

    else:
    #List dimensionality seems to affect the results of the graphs for the training
        eta_values = [5**(-i) for i in range(5)]    #best so far 3
        tol_values = [5**(-i) for i in range(12)]    # 9

    best_eta = None
    best_tol = None
    highest_accuracy = 0  # Initialize with the lowest possible accuracy = 0
    
    #I had to use a negative iterator for to get a higher amount of epochs for the scaled data set
    for eta in eta_values[::-1]:
        for tol in tol_values[::-1]:
            # Train the model with the current eta and tol values
            cl.fit(X_train, t_train, val_set=(X_val, t_val), eta=eta, tol=tol, n_epochs_no_update=n_epochs_no_update)
            t_pred = cl.predict(X_val)
            accuracy = np.mean(t_pred == t_val)
            
            # Update the best values if the current accuracy is better
            if accuracy > highest_accuracy:
                highest_accuracy = accuracy
                best_eta = eta
                best_tol = tol
    
    #print(f"Optimal eta: {best_eta}, Optimal tol: {best_tol}, Highest Accuracy: {highest_accuracy}")
    return best_eta, best_tol, highest_accuracy

'Plotting the MSE-error(Loss)'
def plot_MSE(NumpyClassifier):
    plt.figure()
    x = list(range(len(NumpyClassifier.no_epochs_training)))
    plt.plot(x,NumpyClassifier.list_mse, label="MSE validation")
    plt.plot(x,NumpyClassifier.list_val_mse, label="MSE training")
    plt.xlabel("Number of epochs")
    plt.ylabel("MSE")
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()

'Plotting the accuracy'
def plot_accuracy(NumpyClassifier):
    plt.figure()
    x = list(range(len(NumpyClassifier.no_epochs_training)))
    plt.plot(x,NumpyClassifier.list_acc, label="Accuracy validation")
    plt.plot(x,NumpyClassifier.list_val_acc, label="Accuracy training")
    plt.xlabel("Number of epochs")
    plt.ylabel("Accuracy")
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()

Multi-class classifiers¶

We turn to the task of classifying when there are more than two classes, and the task is to ascribe one class to each input. We will now use the set (X, t_multi).

"One-vs-rest" with logistic regression¶

We saw in the lectures how a logistic regression classifier can be turned into a multi-class classifier using the one-vs-rest approach. We train one logistic regression classifier for each class. To predict the class of an item, we run all the binary classifiers and collect the probability score from each of them. We assign the class which ascribes the highest probability.

Build such a classifier. Train the resulting classifier on (X_train, t_multi_train), test it on (X_val, t_multi_val), tune the hyper-parameters and report the accuracy.

Also plot the decision boundaries for your best classifier similarly to the plots for the binary case.

In [19]:
class NumpyOvRClassifier:
    def __init__(self, base_classifier=NumpyLogRegClass, num_classes=None, bias=-1):
        self.base_classifier = base_classifier  # Base classifier (NumpyLogRegClass)
        self.num_classes = num_classes          # Number of classes
        self.classifiers = []                   # List to store classifiers
        self.bias = bias                        # Bias term for logistic regression

    def fit(self, X_train, t_train, val_set=None, eta=0.1, epochs=100, tol=0.0001, n_epochs_no_update=5):
        
        if self.num_classes is None:                    # Determine the number of unique classes if not provided
            self.num_classes = len(np.unique(t_train))
        
        # Train one binary classifier per class procedure
        self.classifiers = []
        for c in range(self.num_classes):
            t_train_binary = (t_train == c).astype(int)
            
            # Initialize a new logistic regression classifier for this class
            clf = self.base_classifier(bias=self.bias)
            clf.fit(X_train, t_train_binary, val_set=val_set, eta=eta, epochs=epochs, tol=tol, n_epochs_no_update=n_epochs_no_update)
            
            self.classifiers.append(clf)# Store the trained classifier

    def predict(self, X):
        # Get probability predictions for each class (using predict_probability method of base classifier)
        probas = np.array([clf.predict_probability(X) for clf in self.classifiers]).T
        
        # Return the class with the highest probability
        return np.argmax(probas, axis=1)

    def predict_probability(self, X):
        # Get probability predictions for each class
        probas = np.array([clf.predict_probability(X) for clf in self.classifiers]).T
        
        # Return the probabilities for all classes
        return probas


# Instinitaite and tune the One-vs-Rest classifier
ovr_cl = NumpyOvRClassifier(base_classifier=NumpyLogRegClass)
best_ovr_eta, best_ovr_tol, best_ovr_acc= tune_logistic_regression(ovr_cl, X_train, t_multi_train, X_val, t_multi_val)
ovr_cl.fit(X_train, t_multi_train, (X_val, t_multi_val), eta=best_ovr_eta, tol=best_ovr_tol)

Multinomial logistic regression¶

In the lectures, we contrasted the one-vs-rest approach with the multinomial logistic regression, also called softmax classifier. Implement also this classifier, tune the parameters, and compare the results to the one-vs-rest classifier. (Don't expect a large difference on a simple task like this.)

Remember that this classifier uses softmax in the forward phase. For loss, it uses categorical cross-entropy loss. The loss has a somewhat simpler form than in the binary case. To calculate the gradient is a little more complicated. The actual gradient and update rule is simple, however, as long as you have calculated the forward values correctly.

In [20]:
'"Our softmax function for each row of input X'
def softmax(X):
    exp_X = np.exp(X - np.max(X, axis=1, keepdims=True))  # Numerical stability by subtracting max
    return exp_X / np.sum(exp_X, axis=1, keepdims=True)   # Tried to use simpler softmax but gave instability

    

'Categorical cross-entropy loss'
def cross_entropy_loss(y_true, y_pred):
    y_pred = np.clip(y_pred, 1e-10, 1 - 1e-10)             # Clip predictions to prevent log(0) - gives stability
    return -np.mean(np.sum(y_true * np.log(y_pred), axis=1))

def one_hot_encode(y, num_classes):
    """ One-hot encode the labels. """
    return np.eye(num_classes)[y]

class NumpySoftmaxClassifier:
    def __init__(self, bias=-1, num_classes=None):
        self.bias = bias
        self.num_classes = num_classes
        self.weights = None

    def fit(self, X_train, t_train, val_set=None, eta=0.1, epochs=10000, tol=0.0001, n_epochs_no_update=5):
        (N, m) = X_train.shape
        X_train = add_bias(X_train, self.bias)  

       
        t_train_one_hot = one_hot_encode(t_train, self.num_classes)  # One-hot encode the target labels
        
     
        self.weights = np.zeros((m + 1, self.num_classes))  

        # Initialize metrics storage
        self.list_acc = []           # Store training accuracies
        self.list_loss = []          # Store training cross-entropy loss
        self.list_val_acc = []       # Store validation accuracies
        self.list_val_loss = []      # Store validation cross-entropy loss
        self.no_epochs_training = [] # Store epoch numbers
        self.n_epochs_trained = 0    # Keep track of number of epochs trained for

        
        #epochs_since_update = 0

        for epoch in range(epochs):
            self.no_epochs_training.append(epoch)
            
            y_pred = self.forward(X_train)
            
            # Gradient descent weight update
            grad = X_train.T @ (y_pred - t_train_one_hot) / N
            self.weights -= eta * grad

            # Compute training accuracy and cross-entropy loss
            self.list_loss.append(cross_entropy_loss(t_train_one_hot, y_pred))
            self.list_acc.append(accuracy(np.argmax(y_pred, axis=1), t_train))

            # If validation set is provided, compute validation metrics
            if val_set is not None:
                X_val, t_val = val_set
                X_val_bias = add_bias(X_val, self.bias)
                y_val_pred = self.forward(X_val_bias)

                # One-hot encode validation labels
                t_val_one_hot = one_hot_encode(t_val, self.num_classes)

                # Compute validation accuracy and cross-entropy loss
                self.list_val_loss.append(cross_entropy_loss(t_val_one_hot, y_val_pred))
                self.list_val_acc.append(accuracy(np.argmax(y_val_pred, axis=1), t_val))

            # Early stopping condition - similar as to the one in logreg-class
            if len(self.list_loss) >= n_epochs_no_update:
                # Check the last n_epochs_no_update values of the training loss
                recent_loss = self.list_loss[-n_epochs_no_update:]
                loss_diff = np.diff(recent_loss)
                
                # If the changes in loss are all less than the tolerance, stop training
                if np.all(np.abs(loss_diff) < tol):
                    #print(f"Stopping early at epoch {epoch+1} due to no significant improvement in loss.")
                    break  # Stop training

        
        self.n_epochs_trained = epoch + 1

    def forward(self, X):
        return softmax(X @ self.weights)
    
    def predict(self, X):
        z = add_bias(X, self.bias)
        y_pred = self.forward(z)
        return np.argmax(y_pred, axis=1)
    
    def predict_probability(self, X):
        z = add_bias(X, self.bias)
        return self.forward(z)

Part 2: Multi-layer neural networks¶

A first non-linear classifier¶

The following code is a simple implementation of a multi-layer perceptron or feed-forward neural network. For now, it is quite restricted. There is only one hidden layer. It can only handle binary classification. In addition, it uses a simple final layer similar to the linear regression classifier above. One way to look at it is what happens when we add a hidden layer to the linear regression classifier.

The MLP class below misses the implementation of the forward() function. Your first task is to implement it.

Remember that in the forward pass, we "feed" the input to the model, the model processes it and produces the output. The function should make use of the logistic activation function and bias.

In [21]:
# First, we define the logistic function and its derivative:
def logistic(x):
    #x = np.clip(x, -500, 500)
    return 1/(1+np.exp(-x))

def logistic_diff(y):
    return y * (1 - y)
In [75]:
class MLPBinaryLinRegClass(NumpyClassifier):
    """A multi-layer neural network with one hidden layer"""
    
    def __init__(self, bias=-1, dim_hidden = 6):
        """Intialize the hyperparameters"""
        self.bias = bias
        
        self.dim_hidden = dim_hidden # Dimensionality of the hidden layer
        
        self.activ = logistic
        
        self.activ_diff = logistic_diff

        'Part b)'
        self.list_acc = []           # Store training accuracies
        self.list_mse = []           # Store training MSE loss
        'Part c)'
        self.list_val_acc = []       # Store validation accuracies
        self.list_val_mse = []       # Store validation MSE loss
        'Part d)'
        self.no_epochs_training = [] # Store epoch numbers
        self.n_epochs_trained = 0    # Attribute to store the number of epochs trained

        
    def forward(self, X):
        """TODO: 
        Perform one forward step. 
        Return a pair consisting of the outputs of the hidden_layer
        and the outputs on the final layer"""
        
        #raise NotImplementedError

        #step 1: compute hidden layer activations
        hidden_activ = self.activ( X @self.weights1)

        #step 2: compute output layer 
        hidden_outs = add_bias(hidden_activ, self.bias)
        outputs = hidden_outs @ self.weights2 

        #raise NotImplementedError
        return hidden_outs, outputs
    
    def fit(self, X_train, t_train, val_set = None, eta = 0.001, epochs = 100, tol = 0.0001, no_epochs_no_updates = 5):
        """Initialize the weights. Train *epochs* many epochs.
        
        X_train is a NxM matrix, N data points, M features
        t_train is a vector of length N of targets values for the training data, 
        where the values are 0 or 1.
        lr is the learning rate
        """
        self.eta = eta
        
        # Turn t_train into a column vector, a N*1 matrix:
        T_train = t_train.reshape(-1,1)
            
        dim_in = X_train.shape[1] 
        dim_out = T_train.shape[1]
        
        # Initialize the weights
        self.weights1 = (np.random.rand(
            dim_in + 1, 
            self.dim_hidden) * 2 - 1)/np.sqrt(dim_in)
        self.weights2 = (np.random.rand(
            self.dim_hidden+1, 
            dim_out) * 2 - 1)/np.sqrt(self.dim_hidden)
        X_train_bias = add_bias(X_train, self.bias)

        epochs_since_update = 0
        
        for e in range(epochs):
            self.no_epochs_training.append(e)
            # One epoch
            # The forward step:
            hidden_outs, outputs = self.forward(X_train_bias)
            # The delta term on the output node:
            out_deltas = (outputs - T_train)
            # The delta terms at the output of the hidden layer:
            hiddenout_diffs = out_deltas @ self.weights2.T
            # The deltas at the input to the hidden layer:
            hiddenact_deltas = (hiddenout_diffs[:, 1:] * 
                                self.activ_diff(hidden_outs[:, 1:]))  

            # Update the weights:
            self.weights2 -= self.eta * hidden_outs.T @ out_deltas
            self.weights1 -= self.eta * X_train_bias.T @ hiddenact_deltas 
            
            'Part (b: Track training metrics'
            train_pred = (outputs[:, 0] > 0.5).astype(int)
            self.list_mse.append(MSE(T_train, outputs))
            self.list_acc.append(np.mean(train_pred == t_train))

            'Part (c: Track validation metrics'
            if val_set:
                X_val, t_val = val_set
                X_val_bias = add_bias(X_val, self.bias)
                _, val_outputs = self.forward(X_val_bias)
                val_pred = (val_outputs[:, 0] > 0.5).astype(int)
                self.list_val_mse.append(MSE(t_val.reshape(-1, 1), val_outputs))
                self.list_val_acc.append(np.mean(val_pred == t_val))

            # Part (c): Early stopping condition
            if len(self.list_mse) >= no_epochs_no_updates:
                recent_mse = self.list_mse[-no_epochs_no_updates:]
                mse_diff = np.diff(recent_mse)
                if np.all(np.abs(mse_diff) < tol):
                    break

            epochs_since_update += 1

        self.n_epochs_trained = e + 1
    
    def predict(self, X):
        """Predict the class for the members of X"""
        Z = add_bias(X, self.bias)
        forw = self.forward(Z)[1]
        score= forw[:, 0]
        return (score > 0.5)
    
    'Part b)'
    def predict_probability(self, X):
        """Predict the probability of belonging to the positive class"""
        Z = add_bias(X, self.bias)
        outputs = self.forward(Z)
        return logistic(outputs)  # Sigmoid function for probability output

def tune_MLP(cl, X_train, t_train, X_val, t_val):
    
    etas = [0.1, 0.01, 0.001, 0.0001, 0.00001]  # Random learning rates
    epochs = [100, 250, 500, 750, 1000]  # Epochs range
    

    best_eta = None
    best_epoch = None
    highest_accuracy = 0  
    
    for eta in etas:
        for epoch in epochs:
            
            # Fit the model with the current eta and epoch values
            cl.fit(X_train, t_train, eta=eta, epochs=epoch)
            
            # Predict on the validation set
            t_pred = cl.predict(X_val)  
            accuracy = np.mean(t_pred == t_val)  
            
            # Update the best values if the current combination is better
            if accuracy > highest_accuracy:
                highest_accuracy = accuracy
                best_eta = round(eta, 3)
                best_epoch = epoch
                
            #print(f"eta: {eta}, epoch: {epoch}, Accuracy: {accuracy}")  # Debugging output
    
    print(f"Best eta: {best_eta}, Best epoch: {best_epoch}, Highest Accuracy on val: {highest_accuracy}")
    return best_eta, best_epoch

def tune_hyperparameters(X_train, t_train, X_val, t_val, eta_values, tol_values, dim_hidden_values, epochs=100, no_epochs_no_updates=5):
    best_accuracy = 0.0
    best_params = {'lr': None, 'tol': None, 'dim_hidden': None}
    
    for eta in eta_values:
        for tol in tol_values:
            for dim_hidden in dim_hidden_values:
                model = MLPBinaryLinRegClass(bias=-1, dim_hidden=dim_hidden)
                
                # Pass validation set as a tuple (X_val, t_val)
                model.fit(X_train, t_train, val_set=(X_val, t_val), eta=eta, epochs=epochs, tol=tol, no_epochs_no_updates=no_epochs_no_updates)

    return best_params, best_accuracy

  • Reaches highest lvl of accuracy of ~0.90 when epochs > 30, after this the model plateaus
  • Around 90 epochs the accuracy plummits indicating that the model overfits to the provided data

  • large learning rates
  • small validation set size

def evaluate_10_trainings(X_train, t_train, X_val, t_val, optimal_params, n_repeats=10, epochs=100, no_epochs_no_updates=5):
    """Train the classifier multiple times and report the mean and standard deviation of accuracies."""
    val_accuracies = []

    for i in range(n_repeats):
        # Initialize the model with optimal hyperparameters
        model = MLPBinaryLinRegClass(bias=-1, dim_hidden=optimal_params['dim_hidden'])

        # Train the model with the given optimal parameters
        model.fit(
            X_train, 
            t_train, 
            val_set=(X_val, t_val), 
            eta=optimal_params['lr'], 
            epochs=epochs, 
            tol=optimal_params['tol'], 
            no_epochs_no_updates=no_epochs_no_updates
        )

        # Get final validation accuracy for this run
        val_accuracy = model.list_val_acc[-1] if model.list_val_acc else 0
        val_accuracies.append(val_accuracy)
        print(f"Run {i+1}: Validation accuracy = {val_accuracy:.4f}")

    # Calculate mean and standard deviation of the validation accuracies
    mean_accuracy = np.mean(val_accuracies)
    std_accuracy = np.std(val_accuracies)

    print(f"\nMean validation accuracy over {n_repeats} runs: {mean_accuracy:.4f}")
    print(f"Standard deviation of validation accuracy over {n_repeats} runs: {std_accuracy:.4f}")

    return mean_accuracy, std_accuracy, val_accuracies

def just_plot_accuracy(some_list):

def softmax(X):
    exp_X = np.exp(X - np.max(X, axis=1, keepdims=True))  # makes the softmax-activation function stable
    return exp_X / np.sum(exp_X, axis=1, keepdims=True)

def cross_entropy_loss(y, y_pred):
    # Compute cross-entropy loss
    return -np.mean(np.sum(y * np.log(y_pred + 1e-8), axis=1))  # Add epsilon for stability

class MLPMultiClass(NumpyClassifier):
    """A multi-layer neural network for multi-class classification with one hidden layer"""

    def __init__(self, bias=-1, dim_hidden=6, num_classes=3):
        """Initialize hyperparameters"""
        self.bias = bias
        self.dim_hidden = dim_hidden
        self.num_classes = num_classes
        
        self.activ = logistic
        self.activ_diff = logistic_diff

    def forward(self, X):
        """Perform forward step, returning hidden and final layer outputs"""
        # Compute hidden layer activations
        hidden_activ = self.activ(X @ self.weights1)

        # Compute output layer
        hidden_outs = add_bias(hidden_activ, self.bias)
        outputs = softmax(hidden_outs @ self.weights2)  # Softmax for multi-class probabilities

        return hidden_outs, outputs

    def fit(self, X_train, t_train, val_set=None, eta=0.001, epochs=100, tol=0.0001, n_epochs_no_update=5):
        """Train the network with optional validation, early stopping"""
        (N, dim_in) = X_train.shape
        T_train = np.eye(self.num_classes)[t_train]  # Convert labels to one-hot encoding

        # Initialize weights
        self.weights1 = (np.random.rand(dim_in + 1, self.dim_hidden) * 2 - 1) / np.sqrt(dim_in)
        self.weights2 = (np.random.rand(self.dim_hidden + 1, self.num_classes) * 2 - 1) / np.sqrt(self.dim_hidden)
        X_train_bias = add_bias(X_train, self.bias)

        # Initialize lists to track training and validation metrics
        self.list_loss = []
        self.list_acc = []
        self.list_val_loss = []
        self.list_val_acc = []
        self.no_epochs_training = []
        self.n_epochs_trained = 0

        epochs_since_update = 0

        for epoch in range(epochs):
            self.no_epochs_training.append(epoch)

            # Forward pass
            hidden_outs, outputs = self.forward(X_train_bias)

            # Loss and accuracy for training set
            train_loss = cross_entropy_loss(T_train, outputs)
            self.list_loss.append(train_loss)
            train_acc = np.mean(np.argmax(outputs, axis=1) == t_train)
            self.list_acc.append(train_acc)

            # Backpropagation
            out_deltas = (outputs - T_train)
            hiddenout_diffs = out_deltas @ self.weights2.T
            hiddenact_deltas = hiddenout_diffs[:, 1:] * self.activ_diff(hidden_outs[:, 1:])

            # Weight updates
            self.weights2 -= eta * hidden_outs.T @ out_deltas
            self.weights1 -= eta * X_train_bias.T @ hiddenact_deltas

            # Validation metrics, if validation set is provided
            if val_set is not None:
                X_val, t_val = val_set
                T_val = np.eye(self.num_classes)[t_val]  # One-hot encode validation labels
                X_val_bias = add_bias(X_val, self.bias)
                val_outputs = self.forward(X_val_bias)

                val_loss = cross_entropy_loss(T_val, val_outputs)
                self.list_val_loss.append(val_loss)
                val_acc = np.mean(np.argmax(val_outputs, axis=1) == t_val)
                self.list_val_acc.append(val_acc)

            # Early stopping
            if len(self.list_loss) >= n_epochs_no_update:
                recent_losses = self.list_loss[-n_epochs_no_update:]
                if np.all(np.abs(np.diff(recent_losses)) < tol):
                    print(f"Early stopping at epoch {epoch+1}")
                    break

        self.n_epochs_trained = epoch + 1  # Store epochs trained

    def predict(self, X):
        """Predict class labels for input samples X"""
        Z = add_bias(X, self.bias)
        _, outputs = self.forward(Z)
        return np.argmax(outputs, axis=1)  # Return index of highest probability

    def predict_proba(self, X):
        """Predict class probabilities for input samples X"""
        Z = add_bias(X, self.bias)
        outputs = self.forward(Z)
        return outputs
